<subsection xml:id="subsec-applying-graphs-of-straight-lines-in-real-life-situation">
    <title>Applying Graphs of Straight Lines in Real Life Situation</title>
    <p>
        Graphs of straight lines help us visualize and solve problems involving constant change. 
        Whether you're tracking expenses, designing a structure, or analyzing data, linear graphs are powerful tools for making sense of the world.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                 A printing shop charges a fixed setup fee of KSh 5 and an additional KSh 2 for each page printed. 
                 The total cost y (in KSh) for printing x pages is given by the equation: <m>y=2x+5.</m> What is the cost of printing: 
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           <m>0</m> pages
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                          <m>2</m> pages
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           If a customer has KSh 65, how many pages can they print? Show your working.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
               First, draw the graph of <m>y=2x+5.</m>
               
            </p>
            <image>
                <latex-image label="application-example-1">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[y=.5cm, x=2cm,font=\sffamily]
                    % Axes
                    \draw[thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (6,0) node[right] {\textbf{x-axis}};
                    \draw[thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (0,20) node[above] {\textbf{y-axis}};

                    % Grid (light for readability)
                    \draw[help lines, dashed] (0,0) grid[xstep=1,ystep=5] (6,20);

                    % Tick marks on x-axis
                    \foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4,5}
                        \draw (\x,0) -- (\x,-1) node[below] {\x};

                    % Tick marks on y-axis
                    \foreach \y in {0,5,...,15}
                        \draw (0,\y) -- (-0.2,\y) node[left] {\y};

                    % Graph of y = 2x + 5
                    \draw[very thick,blue,domain=0:5] plot (\x,{2*\x + 5}) node[above right] {\textbf{y = 2x + 5}};

                    % Mark a few key points
                    \filldraw[red] (0,5) circle (2pt) node[below right] {(0,5)};
                    \filldraw[red] (2,9) circle (2pt) node[below right] {(2,9)};
                    \filldraw[red] (4,13) circle (2pt) node[below right] {(4,13)};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
             <p> From the graph:
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0</m> pages cost <m>KSh. 5</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>2</m> pages cost <m>KSh. 9</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                To estimate the number of pages that cost <m>KSh. 65</m> to print, we use our equation: <m>y=2x+5.</m>
            </p>
            <p> Since the cost (y) is given as KSh. 65, substitute for y then find x, the number of pages.
                <me>
                    65 = 2x + 5
                </me>     
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    65 - 5 = 2x
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    60 = 2x
                </me>   
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \frac{60}{2} = \frac{2x}{2}
                </me>   
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    x = 30 \text{ pages }
                </me>    
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
   
</subsection>